    "rationale": "This is a classic example of the Ritter reaction. The tertiary alcohol, tert-butanol, is protonated by a strong acid, loses water to form the stable tert-butyl carbocation. This electrophilic carbocation is then trapped by the nucleophilic nitrogen of acetonitrile. The resulting nitrilium ion intermediate is subsequently hydrolyzed during workup to yield the final N-tert-butylacetamide product. The transformation clearly demonstrates the formation of a C-N bond via nitrile capture of a carbocation.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "The substrate is a simple tertiary alcohol, a quintessential carbocation precursor for this reaction. The product is a distinct N-alkyl amide, clearly formed by addition of the nitrile to the carbocation, not by other nitrile chemistries like Pinner (which involves HCl addition to a nitrile to form an imidate) or Houben-Hoesch (which is an acylation of an electron-rich aromatic ring). The use of acetonitrile as the nitrile is standard and avoids ambiguity.",
    "reagents_text": "acetonitrile, sulfuric acid",
    "conditions_text": "Aqueous workup"
  }
}
